{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585512"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:14:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:14:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14987"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14987"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.71,0.06,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7675"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66540"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7675"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14987"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51993"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4908"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"8546"},{"type":"tags","id":"9936"},{"type":"tags","id":"9971"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18759"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18761"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66540"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENatural killer cells are important components of the innate immune system that can recognise and destroy abnormal cells without prior sensitisation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes natural killer cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["They are phagocytic cells","They release perforin and granzymes","They only target virus-infected cells","They require antigen presentation","They only kill through antibody-dependent mechanisms"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENatural killer cells are cytotoxic lymphocytes of the innate immune system. \u003Cstrong\u003EThey are not phagocytic cells\u003C/strong\u003E - this function belongs to neutrophils and macrophages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey release perforin and granzymes\u003C/strong\u003E which create pores in target cell membranes and trigger apoptosis. \u003Cstrong\u003EThey only target virus-infected cells\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - they can also recognise and destroy tumour cells and other abnormal cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey require antigen presentation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - as part of innate immunity, they can function without prior exposure or antigen presentation. \u003Cstrong\u003EThey only kill through antibody-dependent mechanisms\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - they can directly recognise stressed or abnormal cells through their surface receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENatural killer cells are unique in their ability to provide rapid immune responses without requiring prior sensitisation, making them crucial first-line defenders against viral infections and cancer cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Natural killer cells are cytotoxic lymphocytes that use perforin and granzymes to destroy target cells","Natural killer cells can kill targets through both antibody-dependent cellular cytotoxicity and direct recognition","Natural killer cells are part of innate immunity and do not require prior sensitisation","Natural killer cells can recognise and destroy virus-infected cells, tumour cells, and other abnormal cells"],"references":["Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Janeway CA Jr, Travers P, Walport M, et al. Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 5th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2001. Chapter 9, The Humoral Immune Response. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10752/","Mace EM. Human natural killer cells: Form, function, and development. J Allergy Clin Immunol. 2023 Feb;151(2):371-385. doi: 10.1016/j.jaci.2022.09.022. Epub 2022 Oct 1. PMID: 36195172; PMCID: PMC9905317."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51993"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14987"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51993"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T20:46:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T20:47:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7675"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66540"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position"